## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### Pattern Analysis

Your code has **three** patterns that must change for .NET 8:

| API | Problem in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in the
                // ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. The loop condition will exit
                // naturally on the next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals the token — replaces Thread.Abort

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. With cooperative cancellation
            // this means GetNextItem or ProcessItem isn't checking the
            // token. Log a warning — there is no safe force-kill in
            // modern .NET.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

**1. `GetNextItem` must accept a `CancellationToken`** — this is the most critical pitfall. If `GetNextItem` blocks (e.g., on a queue, socket, or `Thread.Sleep`), cancellation won't take effect unless the blocking call is token-aware:

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks forever, ignores cancellation
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    while (_queue.Count == 0)
        Thread.Sleep(100);
    return _queue.Dequeue();
}

// AFTER: wakes up promptly on cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (_queue.Count == 0)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(100); // replaces Thread.Sleep
    }
    return _queue.Dequeue();
}
// Or even better with BlockingCollection<T>:
// return _queue.Take(token);
```

**2. `Thread.Sleep` → `_workerThread.Join`** — the old `Stop()` slept then aborted. The new version calls `Cancel()` first (non-blocking), then `Join` with a timeout, which is both correct and more responsive.

**3. `IDisposable`** — `CancellationTokenSource` owns a timer/callback internally. Always dispose it to avoid leaks.

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Not passing the token to `GetNextItem` | The thread will hang forever on the blocking call — `Cancel()` does nothing if nobody checks the token |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` without the `when` filter | You'd swallow cancellations from *unrelated* tokens (e.g., an HTTP client timeout inside `ProcessItem`) |
| Expecting `Cancel()` to be instant | Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive steps in `ProcessItem` too |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks internal `WaitHandle` and timer registrations |
| Using `Thread.Abort` "just for the force-stop fallback" | It throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 — there is **no** managed force-kill. If you truly need to kill uncooperative code, isolate it in a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` |
